Template Guide
What is a Business Case?

A Business Case is a document which outlines the justification for the start-up of a project. It includes:

A description of the business problem (or opportunity) which exists in the business
A listing of the available options for delivering a solution to resolve the problem
The benefits and costs associated with each solution option
A recommended solution option for approval. ©
When do I use a Business Case?

The Business Case is usually presented by Senior Management within the business to an identified Business Sponsor. It is the first document used in the Project Lifecycle and, once approved, allows the project to be formally defined. Furthermore:

During the development of a Business Case, it may be necessary to undertake a formal Feasibility Study. This process involves a more detailed assessment of the current business problem / opportunity, the various solution options available, the likelihood of a successful implementation for each solution option and the recommended solution option for implementation. The Feasibility Study simply provides the Business Case with more rigor for the solution options presented.
The Business Case is frequently referred to during the project. At each Quality Review point the Business Case is used to determine whether or not the benefits, costs, risks and issues prevalent match those outlined in the Business Case. At the end of the project a Post Implementation Review (PIR) will determine whether or not the project delivered the Business Benefits outlined in the Business Case. In this regard, the success of the project is measured against the ability of the project to deliver the criteria outlined in the Business Case. ©
The next stage following approval of the Business Case is the identification of the project scope within a Project Terms of Reference document.

There are 3 options for this proposed project:

1) Collect cell phones and donate them to recycling companies while educating the public about the responsibility of recycling cellphones.

2) Collect cell phones, donating the non-functional ones to recycling companies, and selling the functional ones.

3) Collect cell phones, sell functional ones, donate non-functional ones to recycling companies, and educate the public about the responsibility of recycling cellphones.

After discussing the options with stakeholders, we think the third option best promotes our initial goals and values.

The project must be actively supported by all team members.  The project must pay for itself by week 10.  All donor’s names, contributions and contact information should be documented with each transaction.  In addition, all accepted cell phones must be tagged with the following information:  make/model, carrier (gsm/cdma), esn/msid/unlock code, last contract (prepay/postpaid), and any technical problems with the device.  It is assumed that every donated cell phone be accepted, be it functional or non-functional.  A phone is assumed to be functional if it::  has an operating battery, powers on/off, keyboard/touch screen and the display is viewable, non-functional otherwise.  Temporary housing will be needed for all cellular devices, and they must be stored in a cool non-freezing temperature.  

When a phone is sold to an individual buyer, the buyer should receive a receipt and a flyer or business card containing the company’s contact information and tips on how to recycle phones in the future.  Packaging materials will be needed for mail shipments.  Recycling companies that we donate to should issue a receipt or certificate of donation.  Form of advertisement is assumed to be a company website made to facilitate the donation of cell phones with email forms, advertise the sale of functional cell phones (also using Craigslist/eBay), display company contact information and to educate the public on the growing concern of recycling cellular devices.  Website is expected to be maintained by team members.

The premise for this project is to help make aware of the importance of cellphone recycling. Cellphones in this day and age have become a pervasive object, carried around by almost everyone. Most people probably have a few old cellphones lying around their house and probably never thought of recycling the old cellphone(s) as it just sits there collecting dust. While this is a bit of an assumption, it can be safely assumed that there are a lot of unused cellphones due to the massive number of people own a cellphone and as new cellphones come out, old ones are forgotten (which at a rate of 100+ new phones coming out every year) it can be safely assumed that there are people willing to recycle their old cellphones. For example, I recently asked some people (friends) what they were going to do with their cellphone once they received a new one; most responded that they’ll just keep it in storage, while a few responded that they might sell it on Craigslist or eBay. Team members have also responded and noted that they as well have old cellphones lying around. With so many cellphones lying around collecting dust, it just adds to a wasteful environment. This is where our project comes in, dubbed Project GreenCell.

Project GreenCell is simple by design: help recycle old cellphones and at the same time educate people regarding the wastefulness of not recycling an unused cellphone. Our group can contact major carriers or providers as well as Recellular to find a compromise in recycled phones and how recycled cellphones should be handled. Our basic plan is to separate cellphones into two categories: working/functional and non-working/broken. Under each category there are several sub-categories to be determined, one such category can be, cosmetic blemish and so on. For the working/functional phones, we might donate it to charity or we might set up a NPO where we can sell the phones at a reduced rate to customers either on eBay or through Craigslist (or simply our own online merchant store) and use the money gathered to help advertise and set up collection places around town and hire people to be at each place to ensure nothing is stolen or lost. To further ensure that each cellphone is handled correctly, every cellphone which leaves our hands is packaged with a colorful information guide as to what to do when the user is done with the cellphone and how recycling helps the environment. A neat idea could be tagging each cellphone with a minor sticker on the back that states: “Return to GreenCell for Recycling”.
We could also separate it further into working/non-working device/battery still operative.  We can ask people for cell phone donations on Craigslist with the incentive that we come pick it up from their homes so they don’t have to do anything and still be able to contribute towards the recycling process.  For non-working phones, we can donate those back to phone manufacturers, because these guys need it most due to the shortage of materials such as lithium, various metals and lead.

Our business vision is quite simple: provide high quality service for a good cause.  Our business objective is to learn how to manage a semi-large project while educating the public about the benefits of recycling old cell phones.  We believe there are other competitors who are too one-dimensional.  For example, one company we researched only donates old cell phones, while other companies collect cellphones for the sole purpose of selling them to increase profit.  We believe there is a middle ground and that is to be as efficient and diverse as possible.
